00:28:54.620 --> 00:28:58.160
Can you just talk about the
evolution of that cause that

00:28:58.160 --> 00:29:00.697
takes a lot of control I think.

00:29:00.697 --> 00:29:02.280
So it's an action
thriller, it's like,

00:29:02.280 --> 00:29:03.920
oh we have to do this car
chase scene or this thing

00:29:03.920 --> 00:29:04.880
through the back alley.

00:29:04.880 --> 00:29:08.520
It was like, no, he's got two
kids and a wife on this moped.

00:29:08.520 --> 00:29:09.270
He can't do that.

00:29:09.270 --> 00:29:11.160
You Top speed's
five miles per hour.

00:29:11.160 --> 00:29:11.910
DREW DOWDLE: Yeah.

00:29:11.910 --> 00:29:14.368
We always ask ourselves, how
do we do the slow speed chase?

00:29:14.368 --> 00:29:18.720
How do we make the really
intense slow speed action?

00:29:18.720 --> 00:29:20.095
That one really
worked I thought.

00:29:20.095 --> 00:29:21.761
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE:
Yeah, we always about

00:29:21.761 --> 00:29:23.580
like, how do you do
the micro-climax?

00:29:23.580 --> 00:29:27.380
Like so many films end in this
bombastic you're on a thing

00:29:27.380 --> 00:29:29.860
and people are jumping off.

00:29:29.860 --> 00:29:31.180
And things are exploding.

00:29:31.180 --> 00:29:35.030
And we're like what's the
smallest, like quietest,

00:29:35.030 --> 00:29:37.130
like what's the micro-climax
version of this?

00:29:37.130 --> 00:29:41.030
And so we always try to think of
this movie really in some ways

00:29:41.030 --> 00:29:43.790
like it starts sort of big
and then it goes smaller

00:29:43.790 --> 00:29:46.530
and smaller until the end.

00:29:46.530 --> 00:29:50.670
And we really like that it feels
more and more intense as you

00:29:50.670 --> 00:29:54.369
go, if you're tightening it.

00:29:54.369 --> 00:29:55.910
DREW DOWDLE: Yeah,
we like that scene

00:29:55.910 --> 00:29:59.160
too in that there's
a moment where,

00:29:59.160 --> 00:30:01.140
you have kind of a rabid mob.

00:30:01.140 --> 00:30:02.820
This kind of mob
violence mentality.

00:30:02.820 --> 00:30:06.190
And then you have a moment with
one individual within that mob.

00:30:06.190 --> 00:30:09.410
And he chooses to
not do what you

00:30:09.410 --> 00:30:12.579
think he's going to do
because for a moment

00:30:12.579 --> 00:30:13.370
he's an individual.

00:30:13.370 --> 00:30:14.860
He's not part of
this larger group.

00:30:14.860 --> 00:30:17.800
And that felt like a really
nice moment to do that.

00:30:17.800 --> 00:30:18.915
KEVIN VLK: Yeah.

00:30:18.915 --> 00:30:20.540
And we'll take some
audience questions,

00:30:20.540 --> 00:30:22.623
if you guys want to pop
in there and ask anything.

00:30:22.623 --> 00:30:26.080
But while they're
getting up there,

00:30:26.080 --> 00:30:32.310
can we talk a little bit about
were there any scenes that you

00:30:32.310 --> 00:30:35.010
guys wanted to get in
there that you couldn't?

00:30:35.010 --> 00:30:36.180
You had to cut for time?

00:30:36.180 --> 00:30:39.820
Or just was this pretty
tight knit once you

00:30:39.820 --> 00:30:42.247
got into the shooting stages?

00:30:42.247 --> 00:30:43.580
DREW DOWDLE: Pretty close, yeah.

00:30:43.580 --> 00:30:44.913
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: Pretty close.

00:30:44.913 --> 00:30:46.050
We barely trimmed anything.

00:30:46.050 --> 00:30:50.180
There was a scene or two of
Pierce that were so good.

00:30:50.180 --> 00:30:52.180
We had a great scene
of him in the hotel

00:30:52.180 --> 00:30:55.969
that once we tested
it, we're like OK

00:30:55.969 --> 00:30:57.510
we're spending too
long in the hotel.

00:30:57.510 --> 00:30:59.500
So we trimmed out a couple
minutes of the hotel

00:30:59.500 --> 00:31:01.430
just to get into it.

00:31:01.430 --> 00:31:04.590
But there was a great
moment with Pierce

00:31:04.590 --> 00:31:07.730
and a woman on the elevator.

00:31:07.730 --> 00:31:10.850
He's so funny.

00:31:10.850 --> 00:31:13.360
We like to joke that like
Pierce was playing the Owen role

00:31:13.360 --> 00:31:15.209
and Owen was playing
the Pierce role.

00:31:15.209 --> 00:31:17.750
KEVIN VLK: That's exactly what
I said to my friend last night

00:31:17.750 --> 00:31:19.520
was that the roles are
completely switched

00:31:19.520 --> 00:31:21.360
and I think that's what
I love the most about it.

00:31:21.360 --> 00:31:22.568
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: Thank you.

00:31:22.568 --> 00:31:24.972
KEVIN VLK: That switch
there was really good--

00:31:24.972 --> 00:31:25.930
DREW DOWDLE: Thank you.

00:31:25.930 --> 00:31:26.640
KEVIN VLK: --you had
that eye on that.

00:31:26.640 --> 00:31:29.139
DREW DOWDLE: Really everything
we trimmed from the first cut

00:31:29.139 --> 00:31:31.690
to the final cut was pre-riot.

00:31:31.690 --> 00:31:34.060
In that kind of early part
of the movie in the hotel.

00:31:34.060 --> 00:31:35.920
We realized we spent a
little too much time there.

00:31:35.920 --> 00:31:38.044
There's some things that
weren't totally necessary.

00:31:38.044 --> 00:31:39.820
The one casualty
that we really regret

00:31:39.820 --> 00:31:41.540
was the Pierce and
the elevator scene.

00:31:41.540 --> 00:31:43.511
But it was connected
to two other scenes.

00:31:43.511 --> 00:31:45.260
And then we could
remove like four minutes

00:31:45.260 --> 00:31:46.093
if we got rid of it.

00:31:46.093 --> 00:31:47.960
So it became based
on a time thing.

00:31:47.960 --> 00:31:50.680
But from the riot to the end,
it changed very, very little,

00:31:50.680 --> 00:31:51.410
honestly.

00:31:51.410 --> 00:31:55.400
Just really turning screws
more than it was anything.

00:31:55.400 --> 00:31:57.640
Scalpel work, not really
any jackhammer work.

00:31:57.640 --> 00:31:58.080
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE:
Yeah, and sort of

00:31:58.080 --> 00:31:59.710
shaping some of those scenes.

00:31:59.710 --> 00:32:01.720
There's a couple
scenes where we just

00:32:01.720 --> 00:32:04.254
wanted a little more
breath in the middle.

00:32:04.254 --> 00:32:06.670
DREW DOWDLE: It's amazing that
we sold it to the Weinstein

00:32:06.670 --> 00:32:08.940
company, and even from
the sale to the finish,

00:32:08.940 --> 00:32:10.884
it was almost exactly the same.

00:32:10.884 --> 00:32:12.550
It was just really,
really minor tweaks.

00:32:12.550 --> 00:32:13.960
And you never know
how that's going

00:32:13.960 --> 00:32:16.584
to go with any distributor once
you have a distributor on board

00:32:16.584 --> 00:32:17.860
sometimes.

00:32:17.860 --> 00:32:19.830
You sign the deal before
you have any idea what

00:32:19.830 --> 00:32:20.996
the creative is going to be.

00:32:20.996 --> 00:32:22.360
And that's always scary.

00:32:22.360 --> 00:32:23.450
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: Harvey
Weinstein bought it.

00:32:23.450 --> 00:32:25.040
He hadn't even seen
the whole movie.

00:32:25.040 --> 00:32:27.780
He'd seen like 10 minutes of
it on a laptop and was like,

00:32:27.780 --> 00:32:29.420
I'm buying it.

00:32:29.420 --> 00:32:30.239
And so then Drew--

00:32:30.239 --> 00:32:32.030
DREW DOWDLE: I flew to
France with the DVD,

00:32:32.030 --> 00:32:34.490
like OK, I hope he likes
the other 90 minutes.

00:32:34.490 --> 00:32:36.686
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: Yeah,
cause it could go anyway.

00:32:36.686 --> 00:32:38.060
You know it could
be like, great.

00:32:38.060 --> 00:32:39.610
You know, now that
I own the movie,

00:32:39.610 --> 00:32:40.776
let's get rid of those kids.

00:32:40.776 --> 00:32:41.600
And let's--

00:32:41.600 --> 00:32:41.800
DREW DOWDLE: PG-13

00:32:41.800 --> 00:32:43.758
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: --put
some dance numbers in.

00:32:43.758 --> 00:32:46.810
You just never know
how it's gonna go.

00:32:46.810 --> 00:32:48.139
And thankfully.

00:32:48.139 --> 00:32:50.180
KEVIN VLK: A song by
Pierce, that would be great.

00:32:50.180 --> 00:32:51.540
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: It's
like and you do that.

00:32:51.540 --> 00:32:53.140
We sit there and do
that to ourselves.

00:32:53.140 --> 00:32:54.200
Like what if he?

00:32:54.200 --> 00:32:55.510
DREW DOWDLE: What's he
gonna want to do it now?

00:32:55.510 --> 00:32:56.270
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: Yeah,
what's gonna happen?

00:32:56.270 --> 00:32:58.280
KEVIN VLK: And it's Harvey,
so we got to make him happy.

00:32:58.280 --> 00:32:59.461
DREW DOWDLE: There's that.

00:32:59.461 --> 00:33:01.710
AUDIENCE: I was curious,
you've had a few movies, now.

00:33:01.710 --> 00:33:04.920
What was the experience
filming in Thailand

00:33:04.920 --> 00:33:06.470
compared to other locations?

00:33:06.470 --> 00:33:08.140
DREW DOWDLE: It was great.

00:33:08.140 --> 00:33:09.760
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: Amazing.

00:33:09.760 --> 00:33:11.570
The Thai crews are incredible.

00:33:11.570 --> 00:33:16.960
Like it was I would say my
favorite filmmaking experience

00:33:16.960 --> 00:33:17.460
ever.

00:33:17.460 --> 00:33:18.900
DREW DOWDLE: For sure.

00:33:18.900 --> 00:33:22.210
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE:
And we didn't want

00:33:22.210 --> 00:33:27.220
to show up as like a big
army of Americans showing up.

00:33:27.220 --> 00:33:31.920
We wanted to become like
a part of the Thai crew.

00:33:31.920 --> 00:33:34.580
And so we brought very
few people with us.

00:33:34.580 --> 00:33:37.800
It was almost exclusively Thai.

00:33:37.800 --> 00:33:42.140
And in some departments
we might have one.

00:33:42.140 --> 00:33:45.350
We had a guy from Canada,
a guy from France,

00:33:45.350 --> 00:33:47.020
and maybe an
Australian, and a Brit.

00:33:47.020 --> 00:33:49.080
DREW DOWDLE: And an
American costume designer.

00:33:49.080 --> 00:33:50.550
We had less than 10.

00:33:50.550 --> 00:33:52.299
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE:
Everyone else was Thai.

00:33:52.299 --> 00:33:53.694
And it was so fun.

00:33:53.694 --> 00:33:55.860
DREW DOWDLE: And they felt
very creatively connected

00:33:55.860 --> 00:33:56.401
to the movie.

00:33:56.401 --> 00:33:58.670
A lot of times when
you shoot, whether it

00:33:58.670 --> 00:34:01.590
be in LA, or Toronto, or
anywhere, a lot of the crew--

00:34:01.590 --> 00:34:01.975
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: Louisiana.

00:34:01.975 --> 00:34:03.141
DREW DOWDLE: --or Louisiana.

00:34:03.141 --> 00:34:06.560
They're there to do a good
job, but they don't truly

00:34:06.560 --> 00:34:07.770
care how it turns out.

00:34:07.770 --> 00:34:09.270
They're there to
collect a paycheck.

00:34:09.270 --> 00:34:11.580
And they're not going to
intentionally do a bad job.

00:34:11.580 --> 00:34:13.480
But they are not
emotionally invested.

00:34:13.480 --> 00:34:17.039
And we felt like this
Thai crew, there's

00:34:17.039 --> 00:34:18.830
so much pride in that
country, and the fact

00:34:18.830 --> 00:34:19.449
that we're shooting there.

00:34:19.449 --> 00:34:21.324
They wanted to make sure
this film was great.

00:34:23.860 --> 00:34:26.082
Most places departments
don't really help each other.

00:34:26.082 --> 00:34:27.290
And usually it's union rules.

00:34:30.230 --> 00:34:32.480
A grip can't help the art
department carry their stuff

00:34:32.480 --> 00:34:34.646
out because there's these
lines between departments.

00:34:34.646 --> 00:34:36.584
And in Thailand
none of those lines

00:34:36.584 --> 00:34:38.250
exist and everyone's
helping each other.

00:34:38.250 --> 00:34:40.010
It was a really
cooperative effort.

00:34:40.010 --> 00:34:42.010
And that was very different.

00:34:42.010 --> 00:34:43.980
It felt like being
in film school again,

00:34:43.980 --> 00:34:46.270
but like having 100
people on your crew

00:34:46.270 --> 00:34:48.821
versus like two people.

00:34:48.821 --> 00:34:50.070
Everyone's helping each other.

00:34:50.070 --> 00:34:53.125
And it was really great.

00:34:53.125 --> 00:34:54.000
Wonderful experience.

00:34:56.177 --> 00:34:57.760
AUDIENCE: So I was
wondering about you

00:34:57.760 --> 00:34:59.926
guys have a lot of experience
in your previous films

00:34:59.926 --> 00:35:00.640
with horror.

00:35:00.640 --> 00:35:03.870
But this is kind of horror in
a very, very relatable sense,

00:35:03.870 --> 00:35:07.282
like real world absolutely
terrified this could happen.

00:35:07.282 --> 00:35:08.740
Could you talk
about some of things

00:35:08.740 --> 00:35:11.114
that you brought from your
previous films that maybe were

00:35:11.114 --> 00:35:14.700
a little more sci-fi-ish
to this kind of real world,

00:35:14.700 --> 00:35:17.287
grounded in reality, experience.

00:35:17.287 --> 00:35:18.870
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE:
That's interesting.

00:35:21.720 --> 00:35:24.787
We actually started before.

00:35:24.787 --> 00:35:26.370
We did a film called,
"The Dry Spell,"

00:35:26.370 --> 00:35:28.560
which was a comedy, which
is where we started.

00:35:28.560 --> 00:35:29.980
And then we started into horror.

00:35:29.980 --> 00:35:33.210
And then people got
to know us from that.

00:35:33.210 --> 00:35:35.620
But both of those
things are you're

00:35:35.620 --> 00:35:37.180
building an anticipation.

00:35:37.180 --> 00:35:39.960
And then trying to pay it
off in an unexpected way.

00:35:39.960 --> 00:35:43.200
And so comedy works sort
of along that paradigm

00:35:43.200 --> 00:35:44.790
and so does horror.

00:35:44.790 --> 00:35:50.640
And this being a
thriller, we do a lot

00:35:50.640 --> 00:35:54.850
of that in this, where
we try to create suspense

00:35:54.850 --> 00:35:56.557
towards something happening.

00:35:56.557 --> 00:35:58.390
And then something
happens you don't expect.

00:35:58.390 --> 00:36:03.456
And now we have to figure
out a new thing to do.

00:36:03.456 --> 00:36:05.580
DREW DOWDLE: Yeah, I mean
our previous three movies

00:36:05.580 --> 00:36:07.140
have a similar through line.

00:36:07.140 --> 00:36:09.970
In that there's characters,
it's kind of a regular day,

00:36:09.970 --> 00:36:12.760
or maybe they're doing something
irregular, but it's a day.

00:36:12.760 --> 00:36:14.110
And something happens.

00:36:14.110 --> 00:36:16.910
And then chaos ensues.

00:36:16.910 --> 00:36:18.380
And they need to try to survive.

00:36:18.380 --> 00:36:20.900
And so "Quarantine" and "Devil"
and "As Above, So Below"

00:36:20.900 --> 00:36:23.715
all had that kind of structure.

00:36:23.715 --> 00:36:25.840
We like to joke sometimes
that our characters never

00:36:25.840 --> 00:36:27.205
change clothes in our movies.

00:36:27.205 --> 00:36:28.174
It's always in one day.

00:36:28.174 --> 00:36:29.340
This time they changed once.

00:36:29.340 --> 00:36:32.122
So we threw our casting
designer a bone on this one.

00:36:32.122 --> 00:36:33.830
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE:
One change of clothes.

00:36:33.830 --> 00:36:35.538
DREW DOWDLE: Yeah,
one change of clothes.

00:36:35.538 --> 00:36:38.990
But for whatever reason, we love
that kind of incidental chaos

00:36:38.990 --> 00:36:41.979
or crisis kind of movie.

00:36:41.979 --> 00:36:43.520
KEVIN VLK: So there
were a few things

00:36:43.520 --> 00:36:47.720
that were kind of hit
points all the way through.

00:36:47.720 --> 00:36:50.180
One was definitely,
stay 10 steps ahead.

00:36:50.180 --> 00:36:52.372
That was pushed
through a few times.

00:36:52.372 --> 00:36:54.330
But the thing was the
little girl always asking

00:36:54.330 --> 00:36:56.390
for the story of
how she was born.

00:36:56.390 --> 00:36:58.556
So can you talk about
where that came from.

00:36:58.556 --> 00:37:03.280
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: That
actually came from my first son

00:37:03.280 --> 00:37:08.080
when my son Henry was born.

00:37:08.080 --> 00:37:11.050
It's like maybe over the course
of your life you see like one

00:37:11.050 --> 00:37:14.600
or two things that
are truly miraculous.

00:37:14.600 --> 00:37:18.930
And for me, I know it sounds
cliche, the birth of my son

00:37:18.930 --> 00:37:19.690
was miraculous.

00:37:19.690 --> 00:37:20.939
And I don't mean it like that.

00:37:20.939 --> 00:37:24.130
He got caught in, not
to get too graphic,

00:37:24.130 --> 00:37:26.320
he got caught in my
wife's birth canal.

00:37:26.320 --> 00:37:29.369
And all of a sudden,
alarms were going off

00:37:29.369 --> 00:37:30.910
and they rushed in
all these doctors.

00:37:30.910 --> 00:37:33.490
And they were going to do
an emergency c-section.

00:37:33.490 --> 00:37:38.840
And the doula who was there
told my wife talk to him.

00:37:38.840 --> 00:37:42.600
Tell him to move through it.

00:37:42.600 --> 00:37:45.620
Or they're going to have to
pull him out in an emergency.

00:37:45.620 --> 00:37:49.630
And so my wife started
yelling to him to,

00:37:49.630 --> 00:37:52.544
like seriously,
through the birth.

00:37:52.544 --> 00:37:54.710
And you could see in the
machines his heart rate was

00:37:54.710 --> 00:37:56.800
crashing because he was stuck.

00:37:56.800 --> 00:37:59.520
And she was talking to him.

00:37:59.520 --> 00:38:03.900
And then you can see on the
monitors like objectively,

00:38:03.900 --> 00:38:05.130
this wasn't in my head.

00:38:05.130 --> 00:38:07.710
You could see objectively
he was reacting

00:38:07.710 --> 00:38:10.430
to her asking him what to do.

00:38:10.430 --> 00:38:13.840
And it was this moment of,
it's probably the last time

00:38:13.840 --> 00:38:14.930
he ever listened to her.

00:38:14.930 --> 00:38:22.060
But you could see he
was at that moment.

00:38:22.060 --> 00:38:24.185
And it was truly miraculous.

00:38:24.185 --> 00:38:25.810
DREW DOWDLE: We always
loved that idea,

00:38:25.810 --> 00:38:28.660
like that idea that
[INAUDIBLE] said that day too.

00:38:28.660 --> 00:38:30.570
I wasn't there obviously.

00:38:30.570 --> 00:38:36.100
But he told me that he knows
your voice, even pre-birth,

00:38:36.100 --> 00:38:37.430
he knows this one voice.

00:38:37.430 --> 00:38:41.141
And that was an idea that
really stuck with us.

00:38:41.141 --> 00:38:43.140
KEVIN VLK: Well, I love
that where it's at cause

00:38:43.140 --> 00:38:44.720
the girl asks several
times during the movie

00:38:44.720 --> 00:38:45.690
to hear the story.

00:38:45.690 --> 00:38:47.120
And he's like, not now, not now.

00:38:47.120 --> 00:38:47.860
And you wait.

00:38:47.860 --> 00:38:49.420
And the audience wants
to know it too, right?

00:38:49.420 --> 00:38:50.290
And I always thought.

00:38:50.290 --> 00:38:52.030
By the end of the movie,
I kind of forgot about it.

00:38:52.030 --> 00:38:52.440
But then like--

00:38:52.440 --> 00:38:53.030
DREW DOWDLE: Good.

00:38:53.030 --> 00:38:53.300
Perfect.

00:38:53.300 --> 00:38:53.720
KEVIN VLK: --I did.

00:38:53.720 --> 00:38:55.320
But then when it got to
the end all of a sudden,

00:38:55.320 --> 00:38:56.802
I was like, oh my gosh, yeah.

00:38:56.802 --> 00:38:58.010
And then they tell the story.

00:38:58.010 --> 00:39:00.051
And it's such a great tie
back to the movie cause

00:39:00.051 --> 00:39:01.999
it seems like she's a fighter.

00:39:01.999 --> 00:39:03.540
And that's what this
whole thing was.

00:39:03.540 --> 00:39:06.581
Like this family who fights
their way through and doesn't

00:39:06.581 --> 00:39:07.080
give up.

00:39:07.080 --> 00:39:10.290
So that was just amazing.

00:39:10.290 --> 00:39:11.720
DREW DOWDLE: Thank you.

00:39:11.720 --> 00:39:11.910
Glad you liked it.

00:39:11.910 --> 00:39:12.650
KEVIN VLK: Kind of one
of the last points.

00:39:12.650 --> 00:39:14.160
Yeah.

00:39:14.160 --> 00:39:17.680
What was the hardest thing to
get right in the entire movie

00:39:17.680 --> 00:39:20.400
just throughout the process of
either writing or shooting it?

00:39:20.400 --> 00:39:22.570
And also what was your
most proudest moment

00:39:22.570 --> 00:39:25.229
on the film that came out
that worked out perfectly?

00:39:25.229 --> 00:39:26.520
DREW DOWDLE: Oh, good question.

00:39:26.520 --> 00:39:27.020
Oh,

00:39:27.020 --> 00:39:28.520
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE:
That's a toughie.

00:39:28.520 --> 00:39:32.800
I'd say there's a
scene near the end

00:39:32.800 --> 00:39:36.380
where, I don't want
to give too much away.

00:39:36.380 --> 00:39:38.150
Sort of the last
clinic, there's a scene

00:39:38.150 --> 00:39:42.730
with the oldest daughter and
Owen Wilson near the end.

00:39:42.730 --> 00:39:45.700
And it's a visceral scene.

00:39:45.700 --> 00:39:47.750
It packs a pretty big punch.

00:39:47.750 --> 00:39:52.650
And that was frankly the
scene I was the scared-- going

00:39:52.650 --> 00:39:55.500
into the movie, I was like,
OK, if this isn't calibrated

00:39:55.500 --> 00:39:58.284
perfectly, it's
not to work at all

00:39:58.284 --> 00:39:59.700
and people are
going to reject it.

00:39:59.700 --> 00:40:00.450
And

00:40:00.450 --> 00:40:02.491
KEVIN VLK: I was also
shocked that the studio let

00:40:02.491 --> 00:40:03.660
that stay in, by the way.

00:40:03.660 --> 00:40:04.280
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: I know.

00:40:04.280 --> 00:40:06.510
KEVIN VLK: I was shocked cause
I've never seen that before.

00:40:06.510 --> 00:40:06.840
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: I know.

00:40:06.840 --> 00:40:08.270
DREW DOWDLE: Well,
If you notice,

00:40:08.270 --> 00:40:10.860
there's literally no
way to take it out.

00:40:10.860 --> 00:40:13.860
Sometimes we design those more
challenging scenes to be like

00:40:13.860 --> 00:40:15.280
you cannot get around them.

00:40:15.280 --> 00:40:17.000
KEVIN VLK: Against a wall and
we have no money for reshoots.

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:18.570
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: If
you buy this movie.

00:40:18.570 --> 00:40:20.080
DREW DOWDLE: You can't go from
the scene before to the scene

00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:20.620
after.

00:40:20.620 --> 00:40:21.540
It wouldn't make any sense.

00:40:21.540 --> 00:40:22.039
So yeah.

00:40:22.039 --> 00:40:23.370
That's kind of our design.

00:40:23.370 --> 00:40:24.360
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: Throwing
the kids off the roof,

00:40:24.360 --> 00:40:26.040
you assume when you see
the trailer, like oh,

00:40:26.040 --> 00:40:27.831
that's going to be the
climax of the movie.

00:40:27.831 --> 00:40:31.756
But that happens like
halfway or a third of the way

00:40:31.756 --> 00:40:32.380
into the movie.

00:40:32.380 --> 00:40:34.160
Like that's pretty early.

00:40:34.160 --> 00:40:38.170
And then when people see that
in their heads, I think they go,

00:40:38.170 --> 00:40:40.810
OK, well, it's only
downhill from here.

00:40:40.810 --> 00:40:41.990
But no, it keeps going.

00:40:41.990 --> 00:40:45.560
And so that was for us sort
of the natural conclusion.

00:40:45.560 --> 00:40:49.070
But it's such an emotional
scene for both the girl

00:40:49.070 --> 00:40:50.400
and for the father.

00:40:53.190 --> 00:40:54.780
And it's gnarly.

00:40:54.780 --> 00:40:59.210
I would say that was
the most challenging.

00:40:59.210 --> 00:41:00.960
That's maybe the
scene I spent the most

00:41:00.960 --> 00:41:03.820
time obsessing over and
trying to figure out

00:41:03.820 --> 00:41:05.011
exactly how to get it right.

00:41:05.011 --> 00:41:06.260
DREW DOWDLE: In editorial too.

00:41:06.260 --> 00:41:08.280
It was exactly what length.

00:41:08.280 --> 00:41:10.850
And that one we spent probably
the most time on I would say.

00:41:10.850 --> 00:41:11.240
JOHN ERICK DOWDLE: Yeah.

00:41:11.240 --> 00:41:11.740
Yeah.

00:41:11.740 --> 00:41:14.709
Because that can't
go on too long or--

00:41:14.709 --> 00:41:16.000
DREW DOWDLE: --or be too short.

00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:17.124
KEVIN VLK: Or be too short.

00:41:17.124 --> 00:41:19.046
DREW DOWDLE: It's doing
the right balance.

00:41:19.046 --> 00:41:20.796
I'd say the one I'm
most proud of is going

00:41:20.796 --> 00:41:23.430
to be kind of a strange choice.

00:41:23.430 --> 00:41:25.136
Because it's not
any of the action.

00:41:25.136 --> 00:41:26.760
It's kind of before
the action happens.

00:41:26.760 --> 00:41:30.577
But there's a scene in the hotel
bathroom between Lake and Owen

00:41:30.577 --> 00:41:31.910
that I always loved on the page.

00:41:31.910 --> 00:41:34.820
And I was always like, OK,
hopefully this connects

00:41:34.820 --> 00:41:36.190
and the performances are great.

00:41:36.190 --> 00:41:37.690
And hopefully the
audience likes it.

00:41:37.690 --> 00:41:39.356
Because it's kind of
an emotional couple

00:41:39.356 --> 00:41:43.060
scene, where she's trying
to suffer in silence.

00:41:43.060 --> 00:41:49.371
And he catches her and he
wants to make sure she's OK

00:41:49.371 --> 00:41:50.870
but you realize
what he really wants

00:41:50.870 --> 00:41:52.990
is her to tell him that it's OK.

00:41:52.990 --> 00:41:54.240
And she won't do that for him.

00:41:54.240 --> 00:41:57.290
And we got more comments on
that scene from people like,

00:41:57.290 --> 00:41:59.160
oh I've had that
moment with my wife.

00:41:59.160 --> 00:42:02.140
Or I've had that
moment with my husband.

00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:04.445
And I don't know I'm
really proud of that moment

00:42:04.445 --> 00:42:06.111
because I feel like
the performances are

00:42:06.111 --> 00:42:07.990
just spectacular and
it really connected.

00:42:07.990 --> 00:42:09.150
KEVIN VLK: Yeah.

00:42:09.150 --> 00:42:10.280
That's really the movie.

00:42:10.280 --> 00:42:11.862
It's real and it's relatable.

00:42:11.862 --> 00:42:12.570
And you watch it.

00:42:12.570 --> 00:42:15.105
And you're like, I hope
that I would act like that

00:42:15.105 --> 00:42:17.230
if I were to be put in that
situation with my kids,

00:42:17.230 --> 00:42:18.570
or wife, or husband.

00:42:18.570 --> 00:42:20.230
It's phenomenal.

00:42:20.230 --> 00:42:21.160
So.

